## Learned Workspace Facts

- Three.js `WebGPURenderer` defaults to **HalfFloat 16-bit** color attachments (not 8-bit) — screenshot-capture color-format assumptions must align with this when comparing WebGPU vs WebGL output.
- Standalone Three.js scenes consuming `gltfCoordinateTransform` (e.g. `kernel-model-view.tsx`) must set `Object3D.DEFAULT_UP`/`camera.up` to `(0,0,1)` and frame `+X,-Y,+Z` — Y-up defaults tip Z-up GLBs.
- WebGL is the default Three.js graphics backend; WebGPU is opt-in beta and tagged in the viewer-settings dropdown via a compact `BetaBadge` from `apps/ui/app/components/release-badge.tsx` (badge appears only in the selector list — never on the trigger pill or closed row); the `'auto'` `GraphicsBackendPreference` value was removed (schema bumped to v4 in `editor.constants.ts`, `parseGraphicsViewSettings` collapses persisted `'auto'`/non-`'webgpu'` values to `'webgl'` while the read-side zod still accepts `'auto'` so legacy payloads parse before migration); auth splashback opts into `'webgpu'` explicitly to preserve the prior "prefer WebGPU when available" behaviour.
- Three.js CAD viewers dual-stack WebGL and WebGPU: `graphics.machine` probes `navigator.gpu.requestAdapter()`, persisted **`GraphicsViewSettings`** includes **`graphicsBackend`**, **`mergeGraphicsBackendWithQueryOverride`** applies **`?graphicsBackend=`** for whole-tab testing; subtree reads **`resolvedGraphicsBackend` / `ViewportCadGl`** (`apps/ui/app/components/geometry/graphics/three/viewport-cad-renderer.ts`). Custom viewport materials ship TSL **`NodeMaterial`** paths for WebGPU with Vitest **`await expect(...).toMatchFileSnapshot`** on **`serialiseStrippedTslGraph(material.toJSON())`** under co-located **`__shader-snapshots__/`** (`apps/ui/app/components/geometry/graphics/three/utils/tsl-node-graph-snapshot.ts` — strips **`uuid`**, replaces UUID-shaped node refs with a stable placeholder, sorts keys). Playwright parity uses **`apps/ui-e2e/src/graphics-backend.spec.ts`** vs **`/e2e/graphics-backend`** (**`apps/ui/public/e2e-graphics/box.glb`** fixture). Policy: **`docs/policy/graphics-backend-policy.md`**. Three.js r181+ WebGPU GTAO: occlusion lives in the red channel only—composite with `vec4(color.rgb.mul(aoTexture.r), color.a)` in `post-processing-webgpu.tsx`; r183+ renames `PostProcessing` → `RenderPipeline` in `three/webgpu`; after `new WebGPURenderer`, use `await renderer.init()` then sync `render()` (not deprecated `renderAsync()`). Static CAD viewports require hardware MSAA (`antialias: true` → `renderer.samples = 4`, inherited by every `pass()`), NOT TRAA — `frameloop='demand'` (policy-bound for the CAD viewport, `three-context.tsx` + `graphics-backend-policy.md`) prevents `TRAANode` from advancing its Halton `_jitterIndex` so a static scene shows a single non-AA'd jittered frame; upstream `TRAANode.js` also requires MSAA disabled, so the two compose. `gltf-edges.ts` coplanar-line depth bias is backend-specific: WebGL must NOT replace `<logdepthbuf_fragment>` (three.js r180 silently renamed `USE_LOGDEPTHBUF` → `USE_LOGARITHMIC_DEPTH_BUFFER` so any `onBeforeCompile` chunk-replacement is preprocessed out — symptom is "inner characteristic edges vanish"; instead multiply `vFragDepth` by an FOV-adaptive bias **inside the vertex shader** after `<logdepthbuf_vertex>` so the upstream fragment chunk produces the correct additive offset and survives future renames); WebGPU uses `tau-renderer.ts` `reversedDepthBuffer: true` so `material.depthNode` MUST use `viewZToReversedPerspectiveDepth` (NOT `viewZToPerspectiveDepth`) and the bias must SUBTRACT (not ADD) — three.js's own `PointShadowNode.js` is the canonical source for the reversed-Z branch; `polygonOffset`/`polygonOffsetFactor`/`polygonOffsetUnits` are the spec-equivalent (WebGPU maps these to `depthBias`/`depthBiasSlopeScale` in `WebGPUPipelineUtils.js`). `infinite-grid-material` light-mode regression on WebGPU is a color-management asymmetry, not a TSL bug: a user `ShaderMaterial` does NOT get auto-injected `<colorspace_fragment>`, so WebGL writes raw linear values to the RGBA8 framebuffer (browser interprets as sRGB → `0.65` linear ≈ `~65%` brightness, accidentally darker and visible) while WebGPU's swap chain correctly converts linear→sRGB (`~83%` brightness, blends into white). The architectural fix is to pick TSL colors that match WebGPU's correct rendering with the same on-screen contrast as the WebGL-bug colors — never band-aid by disabling colorspace conversion. Grid material churn smoking gun: TSL factories that bake uniforms via `uniform(...)` at construction force a full material rebuild whenever their inputs change (e.g. `gridSizes.smallSize`/`largeSize` snapping per camera-zoom decade in `graphics.machine.ts`'s `calculateGridSizes`); the architectural fix is to expose handles to `uSmallSize`/`uLargeSize`/`uColor` and mutate `.value`, eliminating the chained "Declaration name … already in use" warnings + GPU pipeline rebuild leak (`infinite-grid-material.node.ts` is the canonical example — co-located policy test `*.no-named-function-locals.policy.node.test.ts` enforces this). R3F 9.6.1's `state.internal.priority` is a **count** of positive-priority subscribers (NOT a max) — any one of `EffectComposer` / `RenderPipeline` / `SceneOverlay` already disables R3F's auto-render, so the `SceneOverlay` `else` branch is the ONLY thing rendering the main scene when post-processing is disabled (it's not dead code). All CAD viewer / three.js component code lives under `apps/ui/app/components/geometry/` (the prior `apps/ui/app/lib/` CAD scratch space was migrated out — `lib/` is no longer the home for graphics code, only for thin framework helpers like `react-router.lib.ts` / `seems-binary.ts`); new viewport features and React-Three components must land under `components/geometry/graphics/three/` (or the matching `cad/` subtree) so the bundler chunking and SSR-bundle audit stay coherent. Three.js r184+ ships an experimental `examples/jsm/inspector/` (`Inspector.js` → `tabs/Settings.js` → `_loadState`) that touches `localStorage` at module evaluation time — any direct `import` from `three/examples/jsm/inspector/*` will crash the netlify SSR function with `ReferenceError: localStorage is not defined`; the inspector overlay (`three-webgpu-inspector-bootstrap.tsx`) MUST be loaded via `React.lazy(() => import(...))` inside a `<ClientOnly>` wrapper AND the bootstrap module itself must be free of static `inspector/*` imports (every inspector reference goes through a dynamic `await import` that only resolves in the browser), otherwise Vite SSR pulls the chunk into the function bundle anyway. Bottom-edge viewport overlays (e.g. `chat-viewer.tsx`'s section-view / measure / stack-trace / `ChatViewerControls` stack) MUST size to their widest child rather than spanning the full viewport — `absolute bottom-2 left-2 flex max-w-[calc(100%-1rem)] shrink-0 flex-col items-start gap-2` (intrinsic width + viewport-minus-inset cap), with each child opting in to `self-stretch` only when the inner width is needed for `useToolbarOverflow` measurement; `pointer-events-none` on a full-width wrapper is the smelly band-aid (rejected — empty regions still steal hit-testing intent and the wrapper still wastes layout). The same intrinsic-width rule applies to any future floating viewport HUDs so they don't intercept canvas clicks in their empty horizontal padding.; backend swaps (WebGL ↔ WebGPU) use a keyed `ThreeCanvasInstance` child component (keyed on `graphicsBackend`) that fully remounts the canvas + scene + controls on swap — eliminates the `controls-listener.machine.ts` `addEventListener` of `null` crash and the spurious `Graphics context lost` toast that the prior ref-guard helper was papering over (the ref-guard helper + its tests were deleted, replaced by an unmount-safety test that asserts each backend swap creates a fresh canvas instance); `material.clippingPlanes` + `renderer.localClippingEnabled` is the modern THREE section-view approach for both WebGL and WebGPU (May 2026), with capping restored via **Approach 4** of `docs/research/webgpu-section-view-canonical-reference.md` — per-mesh BVH contour extraction (`three-mesh-bvh`) plus `earcut` triangulation of the resulting closed loops into a cap mesh that inherits the source mesh's color; the earlier 3-pass stencil and overlay-render-target approaches both regressed (stencil left objects without caps; FB-indirection produced a visible halo around the WebGPU gizmo — `webgpu-compositor-premultiplied-alpha-halo.md`) so they were superseded; `gltf-edges` lines render inverted on the sectioned side under WebGPU because `Line2` instances skip the standard `clippingPlanes` discard path — the edge fix lives **inside the `line2.material.ts` subclass** (`_clippingMaterial.colorNode` override) rather than in `gltf-edges.ts`, keeping the WebGL path unchanged; color-parity rule for axes/grid/overlays codified as a Color & Blending Parity policy with an S1-S8 reference table — `transparent: true` is declared once for both backends (e.g. on the WebGL `<Line>` axes for parity with WebGPU `NodeMaterial`), grid colors use linear-tuned hex values (e.g. 0xA6_A6_A6 / 0x37_37_37) chosen to match WebGPU's correct rendering rather than calibrating to historical WebGL bugs (the "no historical-bug calibration" rule), and the residual ~10-15 sRGB/channel gamma-vs-linear canvas-blend delta is acknowledged as a known limitation requiring post-processing to fully eliminate (deferred); WebGPU axes-helper z-axis-flip regressions are always smoking-gun bugs in the WebGPU code path (not a shared-config issue) because the WebGL axes path is the established baseline — keep digging in the WebGPU side until the smoking gun is found, never patch the WebGL path to match. Three.js component filenames drop any `tau` prefix (the prefix carries no information at this layer); when both `three` and Tau wrappers must coexist in a module's import scope, alias the upstream import as `Three*` so the type at the call site disambiguates from the local symbol. WebGPU's reversed-Z depth buffer also inverts the painter's-algorithm order for transparent objects, so the renderer routes through a custom `apps/ui/app/components/geometry/graphics/three/reversed-depth-transparent-sort.ts` comparator that mirrors WebGL's log-depth ordering — direct re-use of three.js's default `painterSortStable` produces visibly wrong overlap between the gizmo, capping surfaces, and grid; the Line2 WebGPU subclass owns its own `__shader-snapshots__/gltf-fat-line-webgpu-node-material.json` snapshot under `apps/ui/app/components/geometry/graphics/three/materials/` so the TSL graph stays diff-reviewable across three.js bumps. The viewport renderer and the `screenshot-capability.machine.ts` capture path are NOT allowed to share material/renderer state under WebGPU — captured frames mutate shared GPU pipeline state (notably MSAA/AA settings and Line2 internals) so the next viewport interaction renders with grainy edges and altered AA; the architectural rule is dedicated isolated renderer + material instances for the capture path, never a transient `renderer.setRenderTarget` swap on the shared viewport renderer (full diagnosis in `docs/research/screenshot-viewport-shared-material-state-bleed.md` + `webgpu-edge-line-crispness-gap.md`).
